text.tspan: Notes on senses of polarisation (copy for ray-tracer)

flowRoot.flowPara: For a diverging ray bundle with central axis x, we want to have
'the same' polarisation for all rays // to y. There are two ways to define this:
u1: Give each ray the polarisation with E // to (r x y) x r.

u2: Give each ray the polarisation that has the same p/s ratio as the p/s ratio in the plane perp to the bundle axis. (this is what a polarising surface will do, and also the equivlent to focusing the light to make all the rays parallel first).
The effect is worst at =22.5 and large .
However, the concept of polarisation also depends on
the bundle angle of incidence, so we have two choices:

text.tspan: u1 = (r x y) x r / |(r x y) x r|
For u2, define same p/s ratio as in plane:

flowRoot.flowPara: u2: Same p/s ratio as 'up' has in the plane.

The axial rays, defined w.r.t plane A have a small range of polarisations (0.05) that average to exactly . This is also true for non-axial rays (red) when defined w.r.t their own orthogonal plane (B), but this isn't comparable with the of the axial rays.
Defining non-axial ray polarisation w.r.t plane A gives something directly comparable, but there is now a strong variation around the collection cone (for MSE ~0.3) which doesn't average to .
There seems to be no way to define polarisation in a fundamental, consistent and comparable way.
